attributes.additional_details:
To secure trust in an establishment we feel has been distant & unresponsive, & to avoid a collapse of confidence in the Inquiry's ability to discover the truth, it is fundamental that;

1. The Inquiry is not led by a judge alone. Panel members must be appointed with relevant background, expertise, experience, & a real understanding of the issues facing those affected

2. Legal representatives of bereaved families see all evidence from the start & are allowed to question witnesses at the hearings

government_response.details:
The Government wants to leave our environment in a better state than we found it. The 25 Year Environment Plan that was published on 11 January outlines the steps that will be undertaken to achieve that ambition, including new measures to eliminate all avoidable plastic waste by the end of 2042.
This Government is already a world leader in tackling plastic waste, not only banning microbeads but also taking nine billion plastic bags out of circulation with our 5p carrier bag charge. 

We recognise, however, that more needs to be done to protect our environment from the scourge of plastics.

The Government is looking at how the tax system or charges could further reduce the amount of waste arising from single-use plastics in particular, with the publication of a call for evidence due to be published soon. This will provide an opportunity to assess the environmental impact of plastic straws and other single-use plastic items like plastic-stemmed cotton buds and coffee cups.  

In addition, we: -
•	will remove all consumer single-use plastics (including plastic straws) from the central government estate offices;
•	launched a call for evidence around deposit reward and return schemes for plastic bottles and other drinks containers at the end of last year;
•	will extend the 5p plastic carrier bag charge to small retailers if a voluntary, industry approach is not effective;
•	will work with retailers to explore introducing plastic-free supermarket aisles in which all the food is loose – giving consumers the choice to make greener decisions and promoting the use of less damaging plastic packaging; 
•	will bring forward a bid for the next round of Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund awards later in 2018 to help develop a pipeline of new, more sustainable materials that will have a lower environmental impact; and
•	will do more to help developing nations tackle pollution and reduce plastic waste, including through UK aid.

Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs
